{"commentCount":1,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-11 09:51:11.22","ownerUserId":"63","body":"&lt;p&gt;As others already said, you could understand the sentence as starting with &lt;em&gt;si prega di&lt;/em&gt;, but truly the infinitive is used to express commands in Italian. That is true for sentences like &lt;em&gt;Ritirare lo scontrino alla cassa.&lt;/em&gt; or &lt;em&gt;Non ridere.&lt;/em&gt; which uses a negative and an implicit &lt;em&gt;tu&lt;/em&gt;; while the first is a command for everybody, the last is only for a single person.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h1&gt;Reference&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://tutorino.ca/grammatica/2007/10/26/uses-of-the-infinitive-in-italian.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Uses of the infinitive in Italian&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;","score":3,"creationDate":"2013-11-11 09:51:11.22","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":1171}
{"commentCount":1,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-12 23:57:16.897","ownerUserId":"63","body":"&lt;p&gt;The expression should be understood as &lt;em&gt;essere fuori di testa come un balcone è fuori dalla casa&lt;/em&gt;. In northern Italy, the expression would be understood by everybody; in other regions, the expression may not be understood, and the shorter &lt;em&gt;essere fuori di testa&lt;/em&gt; or &lt;em&gt;essere fuori di senno&lt;/em&gt; is the most used one. What probably makes the first sentence not clear to everybody is that &lt;em&gt;di testa&lt;/em&gt; is implicit.&lt;/p&gt;","score":1,"creationDate":"2013-11-11 10:09:05.117","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":1172}
