{"commentCount":3,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-22 18:50:01.247","ownerUserId":"63","body":"&lt;p&gt;As &lt;em&gt;Lo Zingarelli 2013&lt;/em&gt; says, &lt;em&gt;che&lt;/em&gt; is used to introduce different kind of subordinate clauses. In particular, it introduces a &lt;a href=&quot;http://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proposizione_causale&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;causal clause&lt;/a&gt; when the verb is using the indicative or the subjunctive mood.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Vai a dormire che è tardi.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Andiamo, che è tardi.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://i.stack.imgur.com/WVWLg.png&quot; alt=&quot;screenshot&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;In those sentences, I would use &lt;em&gt;che&lt;/em&gt;, not &lt;em&gt;perché&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;At the same time, in the following sentences I would not replace &lt;em&gt;perché&lt;/em&gt; with &lt;em&gt;che&lt;/em&gt;, even though &lt;em&gt;perché&lt;/em&gt; introduces a causal clause with the verb in the indicative or subjunctive mood too.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Non l'ho comprato perché non mi piaceva.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Non sono venuto perché s'era fatto tardi.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;","score":3,"creationDate":"2013-11-22 18:34:29.193","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":1359}
{"commentCount":1,"lastActivityDate":"2014-08-07 07:00:32.12","ownerUserId":"12","body":"&lt;p&gt;In a previous question I wrote &lt;em&gt;Credo che pressoché &lt;strong&gt;dovunque&lt;/strong&gt; le persone parlino&lt;/em&gt;, but it was changed to &lt;em&gt;Credo che pressoché &lt;strong&gt;ovunque&lt;/strong&gt; le persone parlino&lt;/em&gt;, replacing &lt;em&gt;dovunque&lt;/em&gt; with &lt;em&gt;ovunque&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Can anyone explain the reason why one should prefer &lt;em&gt;ovunque&lt;/em&gt; over &lt;em&gt;dovunque&lt;/em&gt; in that case?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;After consulting some dictionaries. I'm still unsure about what the difference is.&lt;/p&gt;","score":4,"creationDate":"2013-11-22 21:30:36.753","viewCount":126,"title":"Is there a difference between &quot;ovunque&quot; vs. &quot;dovunque&quot;?","tags":"&lt;word-choice&gt;&lt;word-usage&gt;&lt;difference&gt;","answerCount":2,"postTypeId":1,"id":1360}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2014-08-07 07:00:32.12","ownerUserId":"17","body":"&lt;p&gt;They are interchangeable, as they have exactly the same meaning.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;However, since one starts with a vowel and one with a consonant, the usage of one of the two can be preferable in the way they sound.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Credo che pressocché &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;dovunque&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; le persone parlino ...&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;is completely fine and I wouldn't have bothered in correcting it. However I agree that &lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Credo che pressocché &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;ovunque&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; le persone parlino ...&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;pleases my ear a little better, since losing the consonant makes the whole sentence flow more smoothly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;That being said, I think &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;ovunque&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is less common in the spoken language than &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;dovunque&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and it is also a little bit more highbrow.&lt;/p&gt;","score":3,"creationDate":"2013-11-22 21:56:11.363","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":1361}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-23 06:22:02.277","ownerUserId":"63","body":"&lt;p&gt;They are interchangeable, as &lt;em&gt;ovunque&lt;/em&gt; means &lt;em&gt;dovunque&lt;/em&gt;. They are like &lt;em&gt;tra&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;fra&lt;/em&gt;: Although they are synonyms, you avoid some word combinations, such are &lt;em&gt;fra frati&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;tra travi&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;As for using &lt;em&gt;pressoché dovunque&lt;/em&gt; or &lt;em&gt;pressoché ovunque&lt;/em&gt;, Google NGrams shows the latter is used more often.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=pressoch%C3%A9+ovunque%2C+pressoch%C3%A9+dovunque&amp;amp;year_start=1800&amp;amp;year_end=2000&amp;amp;corpus=22&amp;amp;smoothing=3&amp;amp;share=&amp;amp;direct_url=t1%3B%2Cpressoch%C3%A9%20ovunque%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cpressoch%C3%A9%20dovunque%3B%2Cc0&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://i.stack.imgur.com/GOFi9.png&quot; alt=&quot;screenshot&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Furthermore, looking for &lt;em&gt;pressocché dovunque&lt;/em&gt; versus &lt;em&gt;pressocché ovunque&lt;/em&gt;, I get the following.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=pressocch%C3%A9+ovunque%2Cpressocch%C3%A9+dovunque&amp;amp;year_start=1800&amp;amp;year_end=2000&amp;amp;corpus=22&amp;amp;smoothing=3&amp;amp;share=&amp;amp;direct_url=t1%3B%2Cpressocch%C3%A9%20ovunque%3B%2Cc0&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://i.stack.imgur.com/Ax3Xv.png&quot; alt=&quot;screenshot&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;","score":4,"creationDate":"2013-11-22 23:17:07.36","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":1362}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-22 23:59:51.353","ownerUserId":"70","body":"&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Rene&lt;/em&gt; is the part of the body, plural &lt;em&gt;i reni&lt;/em&gt;. But &lt;em&gt;le reni&lt;/em&gt; (only plural) means the lower part of the back and is mostly used in figurative sense. So &lt;em&gt;spezzare le reni&lt;/em&gt; is “to break the back” (probably not used in English), that is, “to defeat”.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;It's similar to &lt;em&gt;le calcagna&lt;/em&gt; that's only used in figurative sense; the heels in proper sense is &lt;em&gt;i calcagni&lt;/em&gt;. In particular&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;avere qualcuno alle calcagna, avere qualcuno alle reni&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;have the same meaning.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;As miniBill says, &lt;em&gt;spezzeremo le reni&lt;/em&gt; was used by Mussolini. Most people at the soccer field don't really know where the phrase comes from and they say it just because they heard it somewhere. Unfortunately, other people do know and use it on purpose. In any case, it's pathetic.&lt;/p&gt;","score":7,"creationDate":"2013-11-22 23:59:51.353","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":1363}
{"commentCount":3,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-23 08:44:00.31","ownerUserId":"212","body":"&lt;p&gt;It is also possible to use Voi instead of Lei. It is rare and used mostly in southern Italy.In some areas you are supposed to use &quot;Voi&quot; also speaking to your parents and also if you are not a kid anymore. This is very rare anyway, I met only 1 person following this rule.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Galateo states that you should use Tu with people of inferior rank, Lei with peers, Voi with people of higher rank and &quot;Essi&quot; with royal family member.Those rules are almost forgotten, it is very common to use Tu always except in formal or business situations as already answered.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;By the way, using the family name to refer to a person is considered more formal and usually used with Lei, i.e.&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;Lei, signor Rossi, venga qua per favore! Tu, Mario, vieni qua per favore!&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;are proper sentences, instead&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;Lei, Mario, venga qua per favore! Tu, signor Rossi, vieni qua per favore!&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;are correct but they sound strange. &lt;/p&gt;","score":6,"creationDate":"2013-11-23 01:00:40.543","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":1364}
