{"commentCount":1,"lastActivityDate":"2013-12-14 14:54:59.927","ownerUserId":"280","body":"&lt;p&gt;The verb &quot;Cosare&quot; doesn't really exist in Italian. Or, at least, it isn't used. To translate the English verb &quot;to do&quot; in Italian, we use the verb &quot;fare&quot;; the verb &quot;fare&quot; is used to indicate generic actions. For example,&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;Facciamo matematica&lt;/em&gt; is a generic form for &lt;em&gt;Studiamo matematica&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;br&gt;In this sense, the verb &quot;cosare&quot; is simply unused.&lt;br&gt;For this reason, Google doesn't give a translation for &quot;cosare&quot;.&lt;br&gt;Used as &quot;che cosa?&quot; or &quot;cosa?&quot;, it is equivalent to &quot;what?&quot;, and its sense is neither of verb nor of noun, because in this context it is an adverb.&lt;/p&gt;","score":3,"creationDate":"2013-12-14 09:52:16.537","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":1478}
