{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2014-01-19 21:44:56.19","ownerUserId":"95","body":"&lt;p&gt;the rule-of-thumb exposed by DaG was proposed by Bruno Migliorini (a famous Italian linguist), and it is widely accepted: if you stick to that rule you won't make any mistake. But until the half of XX century there was no such rule, and one had to look at the etymology of the word: this is why &quot;provincie&quot; (from Latin provincia, -ae) and &quot;ciliege&quot; (from Latin cerasa, -ae) are still used. Just don't use them at school, if you are not prepared to explain why you choose that form!&lt;/p&gt;","score":9,"creationDate":"2014-01-19 11:02:23.227","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":1614}
